Functional Programming is a paradigm shift. Uses declarative code instead of loops. We focus on what's need to be done instead of how will it get done?!

Using stream and reduce to compute the sum in a single line.

import java.util.List;
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        //print each element from a list on it's own line

        List<Integer> ls = List.of(1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8,9);

        ls.stream().reduce(0,Integer::sum); 

    }
}

Core Concepts of functional Programming:

1. Stream: A sequence of elements that support functional -style operations.
Allows processing of data in a declarative way.

2. Lambda Function: Anonymous function (doesn't have a name/return type)
eg: course->course.toUpperCase() is a lambda function.

3. Method Reference:
A shorthand for calling a method.
eg: System.out::println is a method ref: 
or 
x->System.out.println(x);


ls.stream() creates a stream from the list of integers. 








